# Coding Standards

## Philosophy
- Suckless: minimal, simple, frugal. No bloat.
- DRY, YAGNI, KISS. Three similar lines > premature abstraction.
- Each function does one thing well.
- Delete dead code. No backwards-compat shims.

## Style
- Lowercase with dashes for directories (e.g., `auth-handler/`)
- Favor named exports
- 2 spaces indent (JS/TS/Lua/YAML), 4 spaces (Python/C), tabs (Go/Makefile)
- Max line length: 100 chars soft, 120 hard
- No trailing whitespace, final newline always

## Error Handling
- Early returns for error cases at function start
- Raise errors explicitly — never silently swallow
- No fallbacks unless explicitly requested
- Validate at system boundaries only (user input, external APIs)

## Type Safety
- Use TypeScript strict mode when applicable
- Prefer interfaces over types, const objects over enums
- No `any` — use `unknown` and narrow

## Testing
- TDD: write failing test first, then minimal implementation
- Test behavior, not implementation details
- Name tests: `should_<expected>_when_<condition>`

## Environment
- OS: Void Linux (glibc), X11, dwm
- Terminal: kitty, shell: zsh
- Editors: Emacs (straight.el) + Neovim + Cursor
- Font: DankMono Nerd Font
- Theme: Gruvbox Dark Hard (#0d0e0f ultra-dark bg)

## NEVER
- Add comments explaining obvious code
- Create README/docs files unless requested
- Use `console.log` for error handling
- Leave TODO comments without filing an issue
- Import entire libraries when only one function is needed
